# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-flink
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink provides a high-throughput, low-latency streaming engine as well as support for event-time processing and state management.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink applications are fault-tolerant in the event of machine failure and support exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Programs can be written in Java, Python, and SQL and are automatically compiled and optimized into dataflow programs that are executed in a cluster or cloud environment.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink does not provide its own data-storage system, but provides data-source and sink connectors to systems such as Apache Doris, Amazon Kinesis, Apache Kafka, HDFS, Apache Cassandra, and ElasticSearch.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Apache Flink is developed under the Apache License 2.0 by the Apache Flink Community within the Apache Software Foundation.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The project is driven by 127 committers and over 1354 contributors.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Apache Flink's dataflow programming model provides event-at-a-time processing on both finite and infinite datasets.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Apache Flink includes two core APIs: a DataStream API for bounded or unbounded streams of data and a DataSet API for bounded data sets.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink also offers a Table API, which is a SQL-like expression language for relational stream and batch processing that can be easily embedded in Flink's DataStream and DataSet APIs.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The highest-level language supported by Flink is SQL, which is semantically similar to the Table API and represents programs as SQL query expressions.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Upon execution, Flink programs are mapped to streaming dataflows.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Every Flink dataflow starts with one or more sources (a data input, e.g., a message queue or a file system) and ends with one or more sinks (a data output, e.g., a message queue, file system, or database).
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] An arbitrary number of transformations can be performed on the stream.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] These streams can be arranged as a directed, acyclic dataflow graph, allowing an application to branch and merge dataflows.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink offers ready-built source and sink connectors with Apache Kafka, Amazon Kinesis, HDFS, Apache Cassandra, and more.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink programs run as a distributed system within a cluster and can be deployed in a standalone mode as well as on YARN, Mesos, Docker-based setups along with other resource management frameworks.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Apache Flink includes a lightweight fault tolerance mechanism based on distributed checkpoints.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] A checkpoint is an automatic, asynchronous snapshot of the state of an application and the position in a source stream.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] In the case of a failure, a Flink program with checkpointing enabled will, upon recovery, resume processing from the last completed checkpoint, ensuring that Flink maintains exactly-once state semantics within an application.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The checkpointing mechanism exposes hooks for application code to include external systems into the checkpointing mechanism as well (like opening and committing transactions with a database system).
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink also includes a mechanism called savepoints, which are manually-triggered checkpoints.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] A user can generate a savepoint, stop a running Flink program, then resume the program from the same application state and position in the stream.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Savepoints enable updates to a Flink program or a Flink cluster without losing the application's state .
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] As of Flink 1.2, savepoints also allow to restart an application with a different parallelism—allowing users to adapt to changing workloads.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink's DataStream API enables transformations (e.g. filters, aggregations, window functions) on bounded or unbounded streams of data.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The DataStream API includes more than 20 different types of transformations and is available in Java and Scala.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Apache Beam “provides an advanced unified programming model, allowing (a developer) to implement batch and streaming data processing jobs that can run on any execution engine.” The Apache Flink-on-Beam runner is the most feature-rich according to a capability matrix maintained by the Beam community.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] data Artisans, in conjunction with the Apache Flink community, worked closely with the Beam community to develop a Flink runner.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink's DataSet API enables transformations (e.g., filters, mapping, joining, grouping) on bounded datasets.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The DataSet API includes more than 20 different types of transformations.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The API is available in Java, Scala and an experimental Python API.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink's DataSet API is conceptually similar to the DataStream API.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink's Table API is a SQL-like expression language for relational stream and batch processing that can be embedded in Flink's Java and Scala DataSet and DataStream APIs.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The Table API and SQL interface operate on a relational Table abstraction.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Tables can be created from external data sources or from existing DataStreams and DataSets.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The Table API supports relational operators such as selection, aggregation, and joins on Tables.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Tables can also be queried with regular SQL.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The Table API and SQL offer equivalent functionality and can be mixed in the same program.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] When a Table is converted back into a DataSet or DataStream, the logical plan, which was defined by relational operators and SQL queries, is optimized using Apache Calcite and is transformed into a DataSet or DataStream program.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink Forward is an annual conference about Apache Flink.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The first edition of Flink Forward took place in 2015 in Berlin.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The two-day conference had over 250 attendees from 16 countries.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Sessions were organized in two tracks with over 30 technical presentations from Flink developers and one additional track with hands-on Flink training.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] In 2016, 350 participants joined the conference and over 40 speakers presented technical talks in 3 parallel tracks.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] On the third day, attendees were invited to participate in hands-on training sessions.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] In 2017, the event expanded to San Francisco, as well.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The conference day was dedicated to technical talks on how Flink is used in the enterprise, Flink system internals, ecosystem integrations with Flink, and the future of the platform.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] It featured keynotes, talks from Flink users in industry and academia, and hands-on training sessions on Apache Flink.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] In 2020, following the COVID-19 pandemic, Flink Forward's spring edition which was supposed to be hosted in San Francisco was canceled.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Instead, the conference was hosted virtually, starting on April 22 and concluding on April 24, featuring live keynotes, Flink use cases, Apache Flink internals, and other topics on stream processing and real-time analytics.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] In 2024 Flink Forward returned to Berlin, its birth place, for the 10th anniversary.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The conference highlighted the new Flink 2.0 plans, where Java 8 is dropped and a new state backend is introduced.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink CDC was also introduced, allowing no code yaml authored flows.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] There was also a session on Flink's adoption of OpenLineage.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] In 2010, the research project "Stratosphere: Information Management on the Cloud" led by Volker Markl (funded by the German Research Foundation (DFG)) was started as a collaboration of Technische Universität Berlin, Humboldt-Universität zu Berlin, and Hasso-Plattner-Institut Potsdam.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] Flink started from a fork of Stratosphere's distributed execution engine and it became an Apache Incubator project in March 2014.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] In December 2014, Flink was accepted as an Apache top-level project.
[src:apache-flink/apache-flink] The 1.14.1, 1.13.4, 1.12.6, 1.11.5 releases, which were supposed to only contain a Log4j upgrade to 2.15.0, were skipped because CVE-2021-45046 was discovered during the release publication.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] These events may be happening across the various layers of an organization as sales leads, orders or customer service calls.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Or, they may be news items, text messages, social media posts, business processes (such as supply chain), traffic reports, weather reports, or other kinds of data.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] An event may also be defined as a "change of state," when a measurement exceeds a predefined threshold of time, temperature, or other value.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Analysts have suggested that CEP will give organizations a new way to analyze patterns in real-time and help the business side communicate better with IT and service departments.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] CEP has since become an enabling technology in many systems that are used to take immediate action in response to incoming streams of events.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Applications are now to be found (2018) in many sectors of business including stock market trading systems, mobile devices, internet operations, fraud detection, the transportation industry, and governmental intelligence gathering.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The vast amount of information available about events is sometimes referred to as the event cloud.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] 2. the appearance of a man in a tuxedo with a woman in a flowing white gown.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] From these events the monitoring system may infer a *complex event*: a wedding.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] CEP as a technique helps discover complex events by analyzing and correlating other events: the bells, the man and woman in wedding attire and the rice flying through the air.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Commercial applications of CEP exist in variety of industries and include the detection of credit-card fraud, business activity monitoring, and security monitoring.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The CEP area has roots in discrete event simulation, the active database area and some programming languages.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The activity in the industry was preceded by a wave of research projects in the 1990s.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] According to the first project that paved the way to a generic CEP language and execution model was the Rapide project in Stanford University, directed by David Luckham.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] In parallel there have been two other research projects: Infospheres in California Institute of Technology, directed by K.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Mani Chandy, and Apama in University of Cambridge directed by John Bates.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The commercial products were dependents of the concepts developed in these and some later research projects.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Community efforts started in a series of event processing symposia organized by the Event Processing Technical Society, and later by the ACM DEBS conference series.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] One of the community efforts was to produce the event processing manifesto.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] CEP is used in operational intelligence (OI) products to provide insight into business operations by running query analysis against live feeds and event data.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] OI collects real-time data and correlates against historical data to provide insight and analysis.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Multiple sources of data can be combined to provide a common operating picture that uses current information.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] In network management, systems management, application management and service management, people usually refer instead to event correlation.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] As CEP engines, event correlation engines (*event correlators*) analyze a mass of events, pinpoint the most significant ones, and trigger actions.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] However, most of them do not produce new inferred events.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Instead, they relate high-level events with low-level events.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Inference engines, e.g., rule-based reasoning engines, typically produce inferred information in artificial intelligence.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] However, they do not usually produce new information in the form of complex (i.e., inferred) events.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] A more systemic example of CEP involves a car, some sensors and various events and reactions.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Imagine that a car has several sensors—one that measures tire pressure, one that measures speed, and one that detects if someone sits on a seat or leaves a seat.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] In the first situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires moves from 45 psi to 41 psi over 15 minutes.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] As the pressure in the tire is decreasing, a series of events containing the tire pressure is generated.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] In addition, a series of events containing the speed of the car is generated.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The car's Event Processor may detect a situation whereby a loss of tire pressure over a relatively long period of time results in the creation of the "lossOfTirePressure" event.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] This new event may trigger a reaction process to note the pressure loss into the car's maintenance log, and alert the driver via the car's portal that the tire pressure has reduced.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] In the second situation, the car is moving and the pressure of one of the tires drops from 45 psi to 20 psi in 5 seconds.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] A different situation is detected—perhaps because the loss of pressure occurred over a shorter period of time, or perhaps because the difference in values between each event were larger than a predefined limit.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The different situation results in a new event "blowOutTire" being generated.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] This new event triggers a different reaction process to immediately alert the driver and to initiate onboard computer routines to assist the driver in bringing the car to a stop without losing control through skidding.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] In addition, events that represent detected situations can also be combined with other events in order to detect more complex situations.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] For example, in the final situation the car is moving normally and suffers a blown tire which results in the car leaving the road and striking a tree, and the driver is thrown from the car.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] A series of different situations are rapidly detected.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The combination of "blowOutTire", "zeroSpeed" and "driverLeftSeat" within a very short period of time results in a new situation being detected: "occupantThrownAccident".
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Even though there is no direct measurement that can determine conclusively that the driver was thrown, or that there was an accident, the combination of events allows the situation to be detected and a new event to be created to signify the detected situation.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] This is the essence of a complex (or composite) event.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] It is complex because one cannot directly detect the situation; one has to infer or deduce that the situation has occurred from a combination of other events.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] A natural fit for CEP has been with business process management (BPM).
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] BPM focuses on end-to-end business processes, in order to continuously optimize and align for its operational environment.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] However, the optimization of a business does not rely solely upon its individual, end-to-end processes.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Seemingly disparate processes can affect each other significantly.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Consider this scenario: In the aerospace industry, it is good practice to monitor breakdowns of vehicles to look for trends (determine potential weaknesses in manufacturing processes, material, etc.).
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Another separate process monitors current operational vehicles' life cycles and decommissions them when appropriate.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The integration of CEP and BPM must exist at two levels, both at the business awareness level (users must understand the potential holistic benefits of their individual processes) and also at the technological level (there needs to be a method by which CEP can interact with BPM implementation).
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] For a recent state of the art review on the integration of CEP with BPM, which is frequently labeled as Event-Driven Business Process Management, refer to.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Computation-oriented CEP's role can arguably be seen to overlap with Business Rule technology.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] For example, customer service centers are using CEP for click-stream analysis and customer experience management.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] CEP software can factor real-time information about millions of events (clicks or other interactions) per second into business intelligence and other decision-support applications.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] These "recommendation applications" help agents provide personalized service based on each customer's experience.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The CEP application may collect data about what customers on the phone are currently doing, or how they have recently interacted with the company in other various channels, including in-branch, or on the Web via self-service features, instant messaging and email.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The application then analyzes the total customer experience and recommends scripts or next steps that guide the agent on the phone, and hopefully keep the customer happy.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] A time series database is a software system that is optimized for the handling of data organized by time.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Time series are finite or infinite sequences of data items, where each item has an associated timestamp and the sequence of timestamps is non-decreasing.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Elements of a time series are often called ticks.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The timestamps are not required to be ascending (merely non-decreasing) because in practice the time resolution of some systems such as financial data sources can be quite low (milliseconds, microseconds or even nanoseconds), so consecutive events may carry equal timestamps.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Time series data provides a historical context to the analysis typically associated with complex event processing.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] This can apply to any vertical industry such as finance and cooperatively with other technologies such as BPM.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The ideal case for CEP analysis is to view historical time series and real-time streaming data as a single time continuum.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] What happened yesterday, last week or last month is simply an extension of what is occurring today and what may occur in the future.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] An example may involve comparing current market volumes to historic volumes, prices and volatility for trade execution logic.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Or the need to act upon live market prices may involve comparisons to benchmarks that include sector and index movements, whose intra-day and historic trends gauge volatility and smooth outliers.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Complex event processing is a key enabler in Internet of things (IoT) settings and smart cyber-physical systems (CPS) as well.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Processing dense and heterogeneous streams from various sensors and matching patterns against those streams is a typical task in such cases.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] The majority of these techniques rely on the fact that representing the IoT system's state and its changes is more efficient in the form of a data stream, instead of having a static, materialized model.
[src:apache-flink/complex-event-processing] Reasoning over such stream-based models fundamentally differs from traditional reasoning techniques and typically require the combination of model transformations and CEP.
