[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:apache-flink/event-stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
